Global sales improving: \(+7\%\) in July \((+6\% \text{ YTD})\) again led by China \(+14\%\) . US \(+9\%\) and Europe \(+6\%\) also registered solid growth. Korea \(+5\%\) , Japan now falling \(- 3\%\) , EM ex- China resilient \(+4\%\) . Gaining share: GM \(>\) Renault. Porsche stable. Losing share: Honda, MBG, Toyota, STLA (weak in Europe RoW, inflection point in US?), Suzuki, Tesla, BYD, VW (but strong in Europe, EM- ex China), Kia, Nissan Volvo, Hyundai, BMW, JLR. Ford stable. Premium market: \(- 2\%\) in July, still losing share (China). Prices stabilizing across major markets. Fix still the headwinds for EU OEMs

Historical data suggest this information is a strong leading indicator of OEMs quarterly sales growth.

A good leading indicator for OEMs quarterly deliveries release. In this section we compare the MS global sales tracker with company quarterly releases for European OEMs. Historical data suggest that the MS global sales tracker captures a relevant portion of global OEMs sales, being a quite accurate tool to anticipate quarterly revenue growth.

Methodology: we add up information from local auto associations from countries representing \(90\% +\) of global auto sales to deliver a proxy of global auto sales. This report includes both the global summary as well as the evolution by OEMs for the most relevant markets: China, US, Europe (including details for Germany, France, UK, Italy, Spain), Japan and EM- ex China (Brazil, Turkey, India, South Korea).

Global market slowing down: \(+7\%\) in July \((+6\%)\) YTD). China strong, US and Europe also registered solid growth. Korea robust, Japan starting to decline, EM exChina resilient.

China still strong: \(+14\%\) in July, driving global growth. Gaining share: SAIC \(>>\) Nissan \(>\) Volvo, Hyundai. Losing share: BYD (still very strong YTD) \(>VW,\) MBG \(>\) Toyota, Tesla, Honda \(>\) BMW, Ford \(>\) JLR, STLA, Porsche.
US growth accelerated to \(+9\%\) in July. Gaining share: Toyota \(>>\) GM, Hyundai \(>\) STLA, BMW, Ford. JLR, Porsche flat. Losing share: Honda \(>\) Nissan, Tesla \(>\) MBG, VW, Volvo.

Europe saw its best YoY YTD: \(+6\%\) YoY in July (YTD \(0\%\) ). Gaining share: VW (product pipeline showing up) \(>BVD>\) BMW, Renault \(>\) Ford, SAIC, Porsche. Losing share: Stellantis \(>\) Toyota, Hyundai, Tesla, Volvo \(>\) JLR, JP brands.

Japan: July \(- 3\%\) (YTD \(+8\%\) ). Gaining share: Daihatsu \(>\) VW \(>\) Mazda, Toyota \(>\) MBG, STLA \(>\) JLR, Porsche, Hyundai \(>\) BYD, Renault. Losing share: Nissan \(>\) Honda \(>>\) BMW, Volvo.

EM ex- China: \(+4\%\) YoY in July (YTD \(+3\%\) ). Brazil slowing down, Turkey, S.Korea accelerating. India holding up, Mexico dropping. Gaining share: Tesla \(>>\) BYD, Renault, VW \(>\) Ford. Flat BMW, MBG. Losing share: Hyundai \(>>\) Suzuki, Stellantis \(>\) Toyota, Nissan, Honda.

FX: "the" theme of the quarter following a sizeable EUR appreciation. Generalized EUR appreciation vs global currencies, including most final auto markets (translation impact) and competing manufacturing countries (competitiveness). Hedging may smooth the impact temporarily, but FX should be a material negative driver for European OEMs and APs, positive for US, Chinese, Koreans and Indian companies.

Prices: stabilized. Used car prices up \(2.9\%\) YoY in the US and with inflation in Europe, a good leading indicator of what may come next. Several European OEMs have recently increased prices for vehicles exported to the US in response to new tariffs. In China, EV prices stabilized amid anti- involution campaign.

Costs: tariffs starting to show up, but commodities deflation. Tariffs started to show up in summer, but falling prices for most commodities also accelerated last month, particularly in EUR, particularly Tyre- related inputs. The main exceptions have been copper and natural gas. Rare- earth export restrictions from China are also impacting costs, a risk to monitor as tariff negotiations continue.
